    intro_text: 'The dress shirt is the closest garment to the wearer\'s person and the one upon which every other element rests. Its collar frames the face; its cuffs appear below the jacket sleeve; its fabric determines how the whole outfit breathes and drapes. A poorly fitted or wrongly chosen dress shirt can undermine the most expensive suit; the right shirt, correctly fitted and appropriate to the occasion, elevates everything it touches. British shirt-making has a tradition as long and distinguished as its tailoring, producing fabrics and constructions that combine elegance with durability in a way no other country quite matches.',
    style_tips: 'The shirt collar should fit with two fingers of clearance at the neck — neither choking nor gaping, which loosens the tie knot and collapses the collar\nSleeve length should allow exactly 1–1.5cm of cuff to show below the suit jacket sleeve when the arm is hanging naturally\nWhite poplin is the most formal and versatile shirt fabric; pale blue end-on-end adds texture without informality; Bengal stripe is the classic business pattern\nChoose collar style to suit your face shape and the formality of the occasion: a spread collar with a Windsor knot suits rounder faces; a point collar with a four-in-hand is the most classically British choice\nDouble cuffs (French cuffs) with cufflinks are the mark of formal and business occasions; single barrel cuffs are correct for all contexts\nHigh-quality cotton — Egyptian long-staple, Sea Island or two-ply poplin — will outlast and outperform cheaper alternatives in both appearance and longevity',
