    seo_description: 'The definitive guide to wearing a three-piece suit: fit, occasion, waistcoat styling and accessories for the discerning British dresser. William Ashford.',
    intro_text: 'The three-piece suit is the most complete statement in British tailoring — jacket, waistcoat and trousers cut from the same cloth, designed to be worn as a unified whole. It carries more visual weight than a two-piece and a commensurate degree of authority, projecting the message that here is a man who takes his dress seriously and understands its history. The three-piece has enjoyed a sustained revival in contemporary British menswear, driven partly by fashion and partly by a renewed appreciation for the traditions of Savile Row and its satellites. Understanding how to wear one correctly is the mark of genuine sartorial confidence.',
    style_tips: 'The waistcoat must fit closely to the torso without pulling at the buttons — you should be able to slide a flat hand inside but not a fist\nLeave the bottom button of the waistcoat undone when wearing the jacket over it; this is the standard convention and provides ease of movement\nThe waistcoat hem should fully cover the trouser waistband — no shirt should be visible at the waistband from any angle\nFor a formal occasion, keep the shirt and tie classic: white poplin, silk tie, white pocket square flat fold\nThe three-piece reads as more formal than a two-piece — use it accordingly at weddings, formal dinners, client presentations and events where gravitas is appropriate\nFor a smart-casual or creative approach, remove the jacket and wear the waistcoat and trousers together as a two-piece — it is one of the most elegant ways to dress for a warm-weather event or a Friday office',
